ngland"},"en":{"1243–":"1243–Deceased","1239–Male":"1239–Deceased","1264–1296":"1264–1296","1243–Female":"1243–Deceased","1239":"1239","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1453":"1453","1243":"1243","1264":"1264","1263":"1263","1296":"1296","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","England":"England","Halifax, Yorkshire, England":"Halifax, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Toothill","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: (i) locative name from various places named with Old English * <i>tōt-hyll</i> ‘lookout hill’, primarily Toothill in Rastrick (WR Yorks) and perhaps Tootle in Longridge (Lancs), but also Tuttle Hill in Nuneaton (Warwicks), and Tothill (Lincs). There are several further minor place-names of this type that may have contributed to the surname. (ii) locative name, occasionally from Tottenhill (Norfolk), recorded as  <i>Totehill</i> in 1251."],"variants":[{"name":"Tuthill","meanings":["English (Suffolk and Norfolk): variant of <b>Toothill</b>, primarily a Yorkshire habitational name from any of various places called with Old English <i>tōt-hyll</i> ‘lookout hill’, primarily Toothill in Rastrick (Yorkshire) and perhaps Tootle in Longridge (Lancashire), but also Tuttle Hill in Nuneaton (Warwickshire), and Tothill (Lincolnshire). There are several further minor placenames of this type that may have contributed to the surname. Also occasionally from Tottenhill (Norfolk), which derives from the Old English personal name <i>Totta</i> (genitive <i>Tottan</i>) + Old English <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’."]},{"name":"Tootell","meanings":["English:  see  Toothill  ."]},{"name":"Tothill","meanings":["English:  see  Toothill  ."]},{"name":"Tuttle","meanings":["English (Norfolk, Suffolk and Berkshire):","possibly a variant of <b>Thirkell</b>, from the Middle English personal name <i>T(h)irkill</i>, <i>T(h)urkill</i> (Old Norse <i>Thorkell</i>, <i>Thorkil</i>, <i>Thurkil</i>, a shortened form of <i>Thorketill</i> from the god's name <i>Thórr</i> ‘Thor’ + <i>ketill</i> ‘kettle, cauldron’).","variant of   Tuthill  ."]},{"name":"Tutill","meanings":["English:  see  Toothill  ."]},{"name":"Tootal","meanings":["English:  see  Toothill  ."]},{"name":"Tott","meanings":["1  English: relationship name from the Middle English personal name  <i>Tot(te)</i> (Old English  <i>Totta</i>,  <i>Tota</i>).  See also  Totty  ,   Tutt  , and compare Sabyna Tottedoghter’, 1379 in   Poll Tax   (Kirkby Malham, WR Yorks); Radulphus Totusone, 1377 in   Poll Tax   (Frisby on the Wreak, Leics). Some early bearers may belong with (2) or (3).","2  English: nickname from Middle English  <i>tot(te)</i> ‘simpleton, fool’.","3  English: locative name from Middle English  <i>tot(e)</i> ‘lookout hill’ (Old English  <i>tōt(e)</i>). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived on or by a lookout hill, or toponymic, for someone from a place so named, such as Toat Farm in Pulborough (Sussex) and Toat Hill in Slinfold (Sussex).  Compare  Toothill  ."]},{"name":"Tottle","meanings":["1  English:  see  Toothill  .","2  English: relationship name from the Middle English personal name * <i>Totel</i> (Old English  <i>Tottel</i>)."]},{"name":"Tootill","meanings":["English:  see  Toothill  ."]},{"name":"Tootle","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Tuthill  ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":16,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705190,"age":47,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","ju